<webassembly_security_guide>
<title>WEBASSEMBLY SECURITY</title>

<critical>WebAssembly (WASM) runs near-native code in browsers with memory access capabilities. Security concerns include memory corruption vulnerabilities, sandbox escape attempts, import/export function abuse, linear memory exploitation, and WASI security issues. Focus on binary analysis, memory bounds checking, and JavaScript interop vulnerabilities.</critical>

<scope>
- WASM binary analysis and reverse engineering
- Memory corruption vulnerabilities (buffer overflow, use-after-free)
- Sandbox escape techniques
- Import/export function abuse
- Linear memory exploitation
- WASI (WebAssembly System Interface) security issues
- JavaScript/WASM interop vulnerabilities
- Side-channel attacks (Spectre, timing)
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify WASM usage: look for .wasm files, WebAssembly.instantiate calls
2. Download and analyze binary: use wasm2wat, wasm-objdump, or online tools
3. Inspect imports/exports: understand JavaScript bridge functions
4. Test memory bounds: attempt out-of-bounds reads/writes
5. Analyze WASI calls: check for filesystem, network access abuse
6. Reverse engineer logic: understand crypto, auth, business logic
7. Fuzz inputs: test for memory corruption, integer overflow
8. Test side-channels: timing attacks, speculative execution leaks
</methodology>

<discovery_and_analysis>
<finding_wasm>
- Network tab: filter for .wasm files
- Search JS for: WebAssembly.instantiate, WebAssembly.compile
- Common paths: /static/wasm/, /assets/, /dist/
- Files: app.wasm, module.wasm, crypto.wasm
</finding_wasm>

<binary_tools>
- wasm2wat: convert binary to text format
  wasm2wat module.wasm -o module.wat
- wasm-objdump: inspect sections, imports, exports
  wasm-objdump -x module.wasm
- wasm-decompile: pseudo-C code generation
  wasm-decompile module.wasm -o module.c
- Online: wasmer.io, webassembly.studio
</binary_tools>

<inspection_targets>
- Imports: functions from JavaScript (IO, DOM, crypto)
- Exports: functions exposed to JavaScript (API surface)
- Memory: linear memory size, initial/max pages
- Tables: indirect function calls (potential for hijack)
- Globals: mutable state, configuration values
- Data sections: embedded strings, constants, secrets
</inspection_targets>
</discovery_and_analysis>

<memory_corruption>
<buffer_overflow>
- WASM memory is linear array of bytes
- Bounds checking done by VM but logic bugs remain
- C/C++ compiled to WASM inherits vulnerabilities
- Test: supply oversized inputs to exported functions
- Payload: long strings, large arrays, nested structures
- Impact: overwrite adjacent memory, corrupt state, DoS
</buffer_overflow>

<integer_overflow>
- Arithmetic on memory indices (i32, i64)
- Overflow can bypass bounds checks
- Example: size_t index = offset + length; (overflows)
- Memory.grow: test with extreme values
</integer_overflow>

<use_after_free>
- Manual memory management in C/Rust compiled to WASM
- Free memory but retain pointer, later deref
- Difficult to exploit in WASM sandbox but causes crashes
</use_after_free>
</memory_corruption>

<sandbox_escape>
<memory_access>
- WASM linear memory isolated from process memory
- No direct escape via memory access alone
- But: shared memory (SharedArrayBuffer) enables cross-origin leaks
</memory_access>

<import_abuse>
- Injected imports can break sandbox
- If attacker controls instantiation:
  WebAssembly.instantiate(bytes, {
    env: {
      evil: () => { /* attacker code */ }
    }
  });
- Module calls imported evil() → JavaScript execution
</import_abuse>

<side_channels>
- Spectre: speculative execution leaks memory
- Timing: measure execution time to infer secrets
- Cache: observe cache timing to leak crypto keys
- Mitigations: COOP/COEP headers, time precision reduction
</side_channels>
</sandbox_escape>

<import_export_abuse>
<dangerous_imports>
- eval, Function: if imported, enables arbitrary JS execution
- Filesystem access: fs.readFile, fs.writeFile via WASI
- Network: fetch, XMLHttpRequest if imported
- DOM manipulation: document.getElementById, innerHTML

Example dangerous instantiation:
const imports = {
  env: {
    eval: eval,  // DANGEROUS: WASM can execute arbitrary JS
    read_file: (path) => fs.readFileSync(path)  // Server-side WASI
  }
};
WebAssembly.instantiate(wasmBytes, imports);
</dangerous_imports>

<export_analysis>
- Exported functions callable from JavaScript
- Look for auth, crypto, payment processing logic
- Test boundary conditions: null, negative, extreme values
- Reverse engineer to find logic flaws
</export_analysis>
</import_export_abuse>

<linear_memory_exploitation>
<shared_memory>
- Linear memory accessible from JS:
  const memory = new WebAssembly.Memory({initial: 1});
  const bytes = new Uint8Array(memory.buffer);
  bytes[0] = 123;  // write directly
- WASM and JS share same buffer
- Race conditions: WASM writes, JS reads simultaneously
- Confusion: WASM pointer is index into bytes array
</shared_memory>

<memory_inspection>
- Read WASM memory from JavaScript:
  const u8 = new Uint8Array(instance.exports.memory.buffer);
  const u32 = new Uint32Array(instance.exports.memory.buffer);
- Search for secrets: API keys, tokens hardcoded in WASM
- Dump entire memory for offline analysis
</memory_inspection>

<memory_manipulation>
- Write to WASM memory from JS:
  u8[address] = value;
- Modify WASM state: game cheats, bypassing checks
- Corrupt data structures: linked lists, objects
</memory_manipulation>
</linear_memory_exploitation>

<wasi_security>
<filesystem_access>
- WASI provides POSIX-like APIs to WASM
- preopens: directories WASM can access
- Test: read outside preopened directories
- Path traversal: ../../../etc/passwd
- Symlink attacks: follow symlinks to escape
</filesystem_access>

<network_access>
- WASI sockets: TCP/UDP from WASM
- SSRF potential: WASM connects to internal services
- Test: connect to localhost, RFC1918 addresses
- Bypass firewall: WASM makes requests, not browser
</network_access>

<environment_variables>
- WASI environment: env vars accessible to WASM
- Secrets may leak: API keys, paths, configurations
- Read env: getenv() equivalent in WASI
</environment_variables>
</wasi_security>

<crypto_analysis>
<hardcoded_keys>
- WASM may contain crypto implementations
- Keys, IVs, salts in data section
- Extract with wasm-objdump -s -j data
- Search for patterns: repeated bytes, base64, hex
</hardcoded_keys>

<weak_crypto>
- Custom crypto implementations (discouraged)
- Test for weak algorithms: MD5, SHA1, DES
- Side-channel attacks on constant-time violations
- Reverse engineer algorithm for flaws
</weak_crypto>
</crypto_analysis>

<javascript_interop>
<type_confusion>
- JS/WASM boundary has type coercion
- JS number is f64, WASM has i32, i64, f32, f64
- Test edge cases: NaN, Infinity, MAX_SAFE_INTEGER
- Overflow: JS number too large for i32
</type_confusion>

<string_handling>
- WASM has no native string type
- Strings as pointers to memory + length
- Encoding issues: UTF-8, UTF-16 mismatches
- Buffer overflow: string longer than expected
</string_handling>

<function_signature_mismatch>
- Imported function signature mismatch
- WASM expects (i32, i32), JS provides (number)
- Undefined behavior, potential crashes
</function_signature_mismatch>
</javascript_interop>

<validation>
1. Prove WASM binary location and download link
2. Show analysis: imports, exports, memory layout
3. Demonstrate vulnerability: memory corruption, logic flaw, secret leak
4. Provide exploit: JS code that triggers vulnerability via WASM API
5. Impact assessment: what attacker gains (XSS, data theft, DoS)
6. Test in multiple browsers: Chrome, Firefox, Safari differences
</validation>

<false_positives>
- WASM by itself is not vulnerability (it's a technology)
- Obfuscated WASM is not necessarily malicious
- Large memory requests may be legitimate
- Complex imports may be proper API design
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Memory corruption leading to DoS
- Business logic bypass (auth, payment checks in WASM)
- Secret exposure (hardcoded keys, tokens)
- Side-channel leaks (Spectre, timing)
- WASI: filesystem access, SSRF, env var leaks
- Game cheating, DRM bypass (client-side enforcement)
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Download .wasm files early—they may be rotated or removed
2. Use wasm2wat for human-readable analysis—text format easier to grep
3. Check data section for hardcoded secrets—use strings command
4. Memory dumps: new Uint8Array(instance.exports.memory.buffer)
5. WASM from C/C++ more likely to have memory bugs than Rust
6. Test extreme values: -1, 0, MAX_INT, overflow scenarios
7. Browser DevTools → Sources → WASM module debugging
8. Look for custom crypto—red flag for vulnerabilities
9. WASI is rare in browsers, common in server-side WASM (Node, Deno)
10. SharedArrayBuffer enables powerful timing attacks—check COOP/COEP
11. Reverse engineering: wasm-decompile gives pseudo-C, easier analysis
12. Test in worker context: WASM in web workers has different security model
</pro_tips>

<remember>WASM provides near-native performance with strong sandboxing. Real vulnerabilities lie in logic bugs, memory corruption from unsafe languages, dangerous imports, and side-channel attacks. Always analyze the JavaScript/WASM interface and test boundary conditions thoroughly.</remember>
</webassembly_security_guide>
